Potentilla indica is a species of flowering plant in the rose family, native to southeastern Asia.
The plant grows up to 30 cm in height and forms a dense mat of dark green leaves.
The leaves are palmately divided into 5-7 lobes, with a velvety texture on top and hairy underneath.
The flowers are bright yellow with 5 petals, measuring up to 2 cm across and blooming from May to September.
The fruit is a small, dry achene that is dispersed by wind or animals.
Potentilla indica is commonly found in disturbed areas such as roadsides, fields, and wastelands.
It is used as a traditional herbal medicine for its anti-inflammatory and antipyretic properties.
